TEXT(beginproblem());

Context("Numeric");

Context()->texStrings;

$x=non_zero_random(5,10,1);
$y=$x-1;

BEGIN_TEXT

For an exponential model, \(f(x)=P*e^{rx}+b\), how do I get a graph where \(f(x)\) goes to \($x\) as \(x\) gets large, \(f(0)=1\), and \(f($x)\) is at least \($y\)?
$BR
\{ essay_box(8,60) \}

END_TEXT
Context()->normalStrings;

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

ANS( essay_cmp() );

Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_SOLUTION
${PAR}SOLUTION:${PAR}

For the limit to be \($x\), \(r\) should be positive, and \(b\) should be \($x\). 
$BR
$BR
For \(f($y)\) to additionally be at least \($y\), \(P*e^{rx}+b\) should be atleast \(-1\). 
$BR
This happens if \(P\) is positive, or if \(P\) is negative with \(|P|<e^{rx}\)

END_SOLUTION
Context()->normalStrings;

